id not know many people at the H.’s. As I circulated, with a smile on my face and a cocktail in my hand, through the crush, I espied at last the top of my poet’s head and the bright brown chignon of Mrs. H. above the backs of two adjacent chairs. At the moment I advanced behind them I heard him object to some remark she had just made:

